On Tue, 12 Mar 2002, Eric Allred wrote:

> Actually, no.  I was able to tour the Purolator plant in SLC while I still
> lived up there, and believe it or not, they powdercoat oil filters, BUT,
> after the powder is sprayed on, it goes through a very short tunnel  with
> special lights.  No heat, just light made it cure.  He let us put our hand
> in it, and there was no heat (I think the lights were flourecent)  They
> almost looked like black lights.  They were dry to the touch when they came
> out the tunnel too.  It was very neat.

That would be UV (ultraviolet) light beyond the high frequency end of the
visible spectrum.  It it probably wouldn't hurt you for a short exposure,
but longer would give you a nice tan.  Not good for your eyes either.

George


